text: - [Eesha] Hello, all.
This is Eesha Kumnar and Rohit Vashisht.

We are Analytics Specialist
Solutions Architect at AWS.
Today, we'll be discussing a new feature
of Query Editor version two.
The Query Editor version two
is a web-based SQL client application.
You can use it to author and run queries
on Amazon Redshift.
You can visualize your results in charts
and collaborate with your team.
Users often want to know metadata
about queries they ran,
so we added a new Query history tab.

This is located on the left
panel below Charts icon.
I select the Query history tab.
It shows Start time, Status,
Duration of the query, and query text,

as well as Cluster and
Database which it ran.

You can select how much
history you want to see.

In Search, you have the option
to search for query text
or cluster name or database.
Let's try to search by query text: region.

It shows all queries
with text region in it.
Let's try by cluster name:
demolondon.
You'll see all queries for this cluster.

Similarly, you can
search by database name.
It shows all queries for this database.

If you want more details
on a single query,
select the query and go to Actions.

Here, you have the option
to get more query details,

or open query on a new
tab or its source tab.
You can refresh here to get fresh data.

Apart from query history,
we have Tab history.
This is available on Database section.
Click here to get to Tab history.
This tab has no history.
This tab had no history.
Let me select another tab.
You can select a query here
and you can save it if you want.
Or you can also get the query text.

You can choose to open
a query on a new tab
or just simply get details.
That's it.
Thank you so much for watching.
